  "local_port": 35440,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What has replaced CGI (common gateway interface) in today's web?",
  "response": "CGI (Common Gateway Interface) was one of the early methods for generating dynamic web content by allowing web servers to execute scripts on the server side. However, it has largely been replaced or overshadowed by more modern technologies and frameworks that provide more efficient, scalable, and flexible ways to handle server-side logic and dynamic content generation. Some of the main replacements for CGI include:\n\n1. **Server-Side Scripting Languages**: \n   - **Node.js**: A JavaScript runtime that allows you to run JavaScript on the server, enabling high-performance web applications.\n   - **PHP**: Although it has been around for a long time, PHP frameworks like Laravel continue to be widely used for server-side scripting.\n   - **Python**: Frameworks such as Django and Flask provide powerful tools for web development with Python.\n   - **Ruby on Rails**: A popular web application framework that simplifies the development of database-backed web applications.\n\n2. **Frameworks and Platforms**:\n   - **ASP.NET**: Microsoft's framework for building web applications and services, offering robust features for enterprise applications.\n   - **Spring Boot**: A Java-based framework that simplifies the development of new applications.\n\n3. **Web Application Frameworks**: Frameworks like Angular, React, and Vue.js are often used for client-side development, while RESTful or GraphQL APIs built with the aforementioned server-side languages handle the back-end logic and data retrieval.\n\n4. **Microservices Architecture**: Instead of monolithic applications, many developers have moved to a microservices architecture where different parts of an application are developed, deployed, and scaled independently. This often involves using lightweight APIs and containerization with technologies like Docker and Kubernetes.\n\n5. **Serverless Architectures**: Platforms like AWS Lambda, Azure Functions, and Google Cloud Functions allow developers to write and run code in response to events without managing servers, which simplifies deployment and scaling.\n\n6. **Frameworks for Handling HTTP Requests**: Modern web frameworks provide routers and middleware to manage HTTP requests more efficiently than CGI. Examples include Express for Node.js and Flask for Python.\n\nIn summary, while CGI played a significant role in the early days of the web, modern web development has evolved to use more efficient and powerful technologies that facilitate greater scalability and manageability.",
